## Forms

### Field wrapper → `<FormField>`

Every label + input + error in any form across the app:

```tsx
import { FormField } from "@/app/_components/form-field";

<FormField htmlFor="field-id" label={t("field_label")} error={errors.field}>
  <Input id="field-id" ... />
</FormField>

// Works with any input type:
<FormField htmlFor="bio" label={t("bio_label")} error={errors.bio}>
  <Textarea id="bio" ... />
</FormField>
```

`htmlFor` must match the `id` on the input inside. `error` is optional.

❌ Never repeat this inline:
```tsx
<label className="mb-2 block font-sans text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.08em] uppercase text-foreground">
<p className="mt-1.5 font-sans text-sm text-destructive">
```

### Page heading → `<PageHeader>`

```tsx
import { PageHeader } from "@/app/_components/page-header";

<PageHeader title={t("title")} subtitle={t("subtitle")} />
```

Subtitle is optional. Use on any page, section, or modal that needs a heading.

### Multi-step form structure

When a form or flow has multiple steps or views:

```
feature/
├── page.tsx                     ← server component, NO "use client"
└── _components/
    ├── feature-form.tsx         ← "use client" orchestrator — state + handlers only
    ├── step-a-view.tsx          ← pure view, receives everything via props
    └── step-b-view.tsx          ← pure view, receives everything via props
```

The orchestrator is thin — it holds state and async logic, then delegates rendering to views.

